task.summary: First implementation of recognizer, using covariance measure. Not reliable yet.
Peak frequency recognition algorithm. Much more reliable. Needs better design of chirps to improve discrimination.
First attempt at randomly generating the library.
More fiddling with random generation. Now it trends to better recognition.
More fiddling with random generation. Fixed a really problematic bug in the FrequencyTransformer.
Matching now reliable on clean messages. Still not all the way with the challenge message. Now there is a static set of chirps.
Refactor peak list recognizer into its own class so I can work on the BinPatternRecognizer without trashing and tripping on the old code.
BinPatternRecognizer; also fixed issues with codes taking their parameters from the FrequencyTransformer and changing whenever I fiddled with those values.

New recognizer divides patterns into zones and insists that they continue to match over time, so there's a penalty against signals that match great for the first 50% and then not at all for the last 50%. This works WAY better on noisy signals.
Tuned the new recognizer and it gets basically 100% discrimination in the challenge test. There's probably some improvement to be made with algorithm tweaks but it's time to move on!
Decent recognition on the easiest real-world test. Hmmmm
More tweaking, experiments with a new recognizer. Doesn't seem to be working well.
Add automated test regime, fix "last match time" computation error.
Switch to log domain for amplitudes out of frequency transform: the tuning parameters got a lot less sensitive and misrecognition has gone way down, this feels like a good direction so far.
Add new correlation recognizer, fix stupid mistake (disabled AGC/adaptive noise floor in the core recognizer!!), far test case is now recognized well! But the near ones aren't????
